summary: Introduced a refundable tax credit policy to support the start-up costs of new family child care businesses: the Expanding Child Care Access Act would provide a refundable credit of up to $5,000 to cover upfront licensing and startup expenses for in-home family child care providers once they obtain state licensure or registration. At a February 2025 town hall, he also criticized proposals that would cut programs like Medicaid and SNAP in order to provide "an enormous tax break to the wealthiest," and said Democrats will fight those tax-cut-driven cuts.

Gill led the House in passing H.J.Res.142 to disapprove the D.C. Council's temporary tax law that would have decoupled the District from key provisions of the Working Families Tax Cut Act. He argued the resolution was necessary to ensure D.C. residents—particularly service workers—receive federal tax relief such as no tax on tips and overtime, an increased standard deduction, and expanded business expensing. He framed the action as protecting hardworking families' and small businesses' ability to keep more of their own money and joined Senate Republicans and allied groups in opposing the D.C. Council's interference under the Home Rule Act. Upon his January 3, 2025 swearing-in Gill also reiterated a general pledge to 'cut taxes and regulations' as an early priority. In July 2025 he voted to pass President Trump's One Big Beautiful Bill, which he praised for delivering 'historic tax cuts for working-class families' as part of a package that also funds border enforcement and deportations. He also voted in favor of the February 26, 2025 House budget resolution to extend President Trump's tax cuts, backing measures intended to preserve and advance Trump's tax agenda.

Supported H.R.1 as a major tax-cut package described in his release as the largest tax cut in American history; advocated specific provisions including 'No Taxes on Tips,' 'No Taxes on Overtime,' and 'Historic Tax Relief for our senior citizens.' More recently has championed President Trump's Working Families Tax Cut at local events, presenting the new tax relief as a continuation of his agenda to reward American workers and small businesses and support local manufacturing.
